<div class="main_content">
    <h2>British in Afghanistan</h2>
    <p>One of Britain's major exports from India was opium, and by 1770 they had a manopoly on the product, and started to also grow it in Afghanistan. In 1839, Britain send 12,000 troops to the country, to remove the current king, Dost Mohammad, from power because they suspected him of being too friendly with Russia, which may have endangered their drug trade.</p>
    <div class="sub_content">
        <h3>Anglo-Afghan War</h3>
        <p>The Anglo-Afghan War was fought between the British East India Company and Afghanistan, starting in 1839 and lasting three years. In December of 1938, 21,000 British and Indian troops led by John Keane set out towards Afghanistan. By April 1839, these forces had crossed the Bolan Pass and made it to Quetta, in Afghanistan. There was a sneak attack led by the British in July of 1839, on the fortress of Ghazni. They blew up a city gate, marched in, and won a decisive victory. The Afghans lost about 500 men.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="sub_content">
        <img class="leftimage" style="max-width: 15%;" src="/images/dostmohammad.jpg" alt="Dost Mohammad Khan">
        <p><strong>Dost Mohammad Khan</strong> was an Afghan leader during the First Afghan War, and helped lead the country in battle against the British and Indian forces.</p>
    </div>
</div>
